---


Author Name: **Kevin Thompson**
Original Redmine Issue: 902 from https://www.veripool.org
Original Date: 2015-03-25


---

Hello,

I believe that this is more of a request for an enhancement than a fix per-se.

To begin with, if I have a module with this signature:

module v1 #(parameter WIDTH = 204)
(
     input                                 Clk,
     input                                 nReset,
     input [WIDTH-1:0]         wData, 
     output reg [WIDTH-1:0] rData 
);
:
:
:
endmodule

Within another Verilog module, it is possible to create two instances of “v1” with differing widths:

module top_v();

     parameter WIDTH=128;

     reg [WIDTH-1:0] my_data_in;
     wire [WIDTH-1:0] my_data_out;

     v1 #(.WIDTH(WIDTH)) 
         my_v1(.Clk(Clk), .nReset(nReset), .wData(my_data_in), .rData(my_data_out) );

     reg [32-1:0] more_data_in;
     wire [32-1:0] more_data_out;

     v1 #(.WIDTH(32)) 
         more_v1(.Clk(Clk),
              .nReset(nReset),
              .wData(more_data_in),
              .rData(more_data_out) );
:
:
:
endmodule

Within the C++ code however, once the module v1 is translated, the data width is “locked in”. Would it be possible to add template functionality to the translated C++ module, e.g. for “module v1” above:




template <std::size_t width=204> // or whatever WIDTH is defined as.
struct v1 : public sc_module
{
	sc_in<sc_bv<width> >    wData;
	sc_out< sc_bv<width> > rData;
:
:
:
}

In another top C++ module this would allow one to do:

v1<214> first_inst;
v1<32>   second_inst;
v1<>       def_inst;

I realize that this would be a design change but perhaps instead of the being the default behavior when parameters are present in Verilog, it could be a command line switch, e.g. --templated-parameters, and then let the user deal with the templated code. The –templated-parameters switch of course would only be used when –pins-bv is also included.

Thank you.
